f=Cybersecurity/warden/marketplace/third-party-risk/SKILL.md · in=Evaluate third-party vendors systematically comparing full cost vendor relationship against risks, performance, strategic fit business makes procurement decisions clear eyes clear recommendation. · p=Vendor decisions made price alone, demo alone, relationship alone, regularly turn surprises: hidden migration costs, security gaps one checked, SLA failures aren't enforceable, lock-in becomes clear it's late back out. skill exists prevent surprises putting significant vendor decision through structured evaluation, business compare apples apples know exactly what it's signing for. · wu=new vendor evaluated significant contract (typically $5K+/year touching sensitive data)., existing vendor renewal re-evaluated rather auto-renewed., Something went wrong vendor business needs assess whether escalate, renegotiate, replace., shortlist vendors exists business needs structured comparison make final selection., skill covers vendor selection renewal evaluation. cover contract negotiation, compliance audits existing vendors, procurement process design separate workflows. · st:/ Protocol=`GATHER (vendor details, pricing, and scope of engagement) \· → ANALYZE COST (TCO: subscription + implementation + migration + training + exit costs) \· → ASSESS RISK (financial stability, security/compliance posture, concentration risk, lock-in) \· → EVALUATE PERFORMANCE (SLA compliance, support responsiveness, uptime history — for renewals) \· → COMPARE (side-by-side matrix for shortlists, or current vs market for single-vendor evaluations)` · h3:Phase Gather information=Start collecting basic facts about vendor engagement: · h3:Phase Gather information=**Vendor name**, product/service evaluated, business unit team proposing it., **Scope engagement**: what vendor do, what data access, what systems integrate with., **Pricing model total annual cost** proposed. shortlist, collect vendor. · h3:Phase Gather information=key information missing team can't articulate what data vendor touch, pricing "we haven't asked yet" flag it. evaluation incomplete information worse evaluation; creates false confidence. · h3:Phase Analyze total cost ownership (TCO)=Cost subscription line. Calculate full TCO across: · h3:Phase Analyze total cost ownership (TCO)=**Subscription/licensing** base annual monthly cost, including any per-seat overage charges., **Implementation migration** estimated internal engineering time, data migration effort, integration work. Get rough engineering-day estimate team possible., **Training** cost train team new tool platform., **Ongoing operations** any incremental headcount operational overhead vendor introduces., **Exit cost** what cost move off vendor: data export fees, migration time future replacement, any contractual penalties. · h3:Phase Analyze total cost ownership (TCO)=renewals, flag any **price increases** since last term any **scope creep** wasn't reflected original pricing. · h3:Phase Assess risk=Evaluate vendor across four risk dimensions: **1. Financial stability** · h3:Phase Assess risk=long vendor business? What's their funding stage public financial health?, they reliant small number customers? High concentration risk them concentration risk you., Any recent layoffs, leadership turnover, negative financial signals? (Public information don't ask financials you're entitled to.) · h3:Phase Assess risk=**2. Security compliance posture** · h3:Phase Assess risk=What certifications they hold? (SOC Type II, ISO 27001, FedRAMP, etc.) Check scope SOC report excludes service you're buying worth less one covers it., they published security page, trust center, shared responsibility model?, they public breach last years? they handle it?, What data they process store? their subprocessor list include any names raise flags?, *Note: evaluator's assessment based public info vendor's trust center. replacement full security review warden. High-risk vendors additionally assessed through warden's third-party-risk (the dedicated skill).* · h3:Phase Assess risk=**3. Concentration risk** · h3:Phase Assess risk=switching away vendor hard? hard? Nearly impossible? (Data portability, API dependency, workflow embedding rate it.), vendor competitors market realistic alternative prices rise quality drops?, SaaS: you export your data standard format without professional-services help? · h3:Phase Assess risk=**4. Lock-in risk** · h3:Phase Assess risk=Contract terms: minimum commitment period, auto-renewal clauses, termination-for-convenience penalties., early-termination fees? they calculated?, Data egress API access restrictions make leaving painful. · h3:Phase Evaluate performance (renewals only)=existing vendors re-evaluated: · h3:Phase Evaluate performance (renewals only)=**SLA compliance**: vendor met uptime/performance SLAs over current term? breaches, credits paid without fight?, **Support responsiveness**: Ticket response times, severity handling, whether support quality changed over term., **Uptime reliability**: Any major outages? frequent? long? communication good during them?, **Relationship trend**: account management relationship improved, stayed same, deteriorated? · h3:Phase Evaluate performance (renewals only)=new evaluations, phase replaced reference calls analyst reports available. · h3:Phase Compare (shortlist) benchmark (single vendor)=**For shortlists**: Build comparison matrix across dimensions above cost, risk, performance. Winner isn't always cheapest; weight business's priorities., **For single-vendor evaluations**: Benchmark their offering against market. What comparable vendors charge? What features they lack? vendor priced fairly premium incumbency? · h3:Phase Compare (shortlist) benchmark (single vendor)=vendor option (no realistic alternative), state explicitly "sole source" risk finding itself flagged concentration risk finding. · h3:Phase 6 — Recommend=Deliver clear recommendation supporting rationale: · h3:Phase 6 — Recommend=**Proceed** vendor good fit. Include any conditions negotiation points., **Negotiate** vendor work specific terms need improvement. List top things negotiate (price, contract terms, security addenda)., **Pass** vendor good fit. State primary reason(s) clearly. · of=`## Vendor Review: [vendor name] — [product/service] \· TCO: $[annual total] \· Term: [length] \· Risk assessment: [Low/Medium/High — with key flags] \· Financial: [assessment] \· Security/Compliance: [assessment] (see also: warden third-party-risk for deep security review)` · pr=**TCO over sticker price.** cheapest vendor expensive after migration exit costs. **Risk before price.** vendor that's cheap unstable, insecure, impossible leave bargain. **Recommend, don't decide.** evaluator's job clear, evidence-backed recommendation; procurement decision belongs business. **Flag unknown information.** team can't tell you what data vendor touch, say don't assume "it's probably fine." **Comparison point.** single-vendor evaluation benchmark against market; shortlist evaluation head-to-head. better evaluating vacuum. · f=**No pricing info yet** evaluate risk fit alone; flag cost TBD recommendation conditional price within acceptable band., **No security certifications** raise risk score don't automatically reject; smaller vendors compensating controls without cert budget. Flag warden's third-party-risk deep dive., **Sole source** flag concentration risk; recommendation becomes "proceed mitigate dependency" rather comparison-based choice., **Incomplete information** state what's missing critical is. Don't manufacture recommendation insufficient data. · b:with Other Skills=**warden's risk-register**: vendor risk scores feed risk register; accepted vendor risk routes board., **warden's security-policy-framework**: vendor controls map ISMS; vendor without DPA PII framework gap., **vendor-ai-risk** (supplementary marketplace skill): AI-specific vendor assessments, use vendor-ai-risk alongside skill dimensions (data training rights, model behavior, output ownership)., **cortex (Cybersecurity)**: vendor breach triggers immediate coordination., **veil (Cybersecurity)**: breach-notification obligations fire vendor incidents.